Dataset for this report is retrived through the Data Services of ICAO (International Civil Aviation Organization). This dataset includes data about official accidents (should not be mistaken with incidents) between Jan 2008 and March 2021 happened around the world.¶

Data: https://www.icao.int/safety/iStars/Pages/API-Data-Service-new.aspx

For this dataset, the Injury level of the accidents will only be classified into 2 types: Fatal (number of Fatalities > 0) and Non-Fatal (number of Fatalities = 0)¶
In [5]:
df.loc[df["Fatalities"].isna(), ["Fatalities"]] = 0
In [6]:
df.loc[df["Fatalities"] > 0, ["InjuryLevel"]] = "Fatal"
df.loc[df["Fatalities"] == 0, ["InjuryLevel"]] = "Non-Fatal"
Plot out the ratio to generally see the distribution of the 2 types of Injury levels among all Aviation Accidents¶
In [7]:
injury_levels = df["InjuryLevel"].unique()
injury_levels_percentages = []
for level in injury_levels:
    injury_levels_percentages.append(df[df["InjuryLevel"] == level]["InjuryLevel"].count() / df["InjuryLevel"].count())

plt.rcParams.update({'font.size' : 10})    

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (5, 5))
ax.set_title("Injury Level of Aviation Accidens From 2008 To March 2021\nData: ICAO")
ax.pie(injury_levels_percentages, labels=injury_levels, autopct='%1.2f%%',
       shadow=True, startangle=90)
ax.axis('equal')
plt.show()

Observation 1: Clearly, the number of Non-Fatal accidents is much more than Fatal accidents. Total number of Fatal accidents make up to no more than 12% of the whole dataset.¶

In [9]:
def add_value_labels(ax, spacing=5):
    for rect in ax.patches:
        y_value = rect.get_height()
        x_value = rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2
        space = spacing
        va = 'bottom'
        label = "{:d}".format(y_value)

        ax.annotate(
            label,                      
            (x_value, y_value),         
            xytext=(0, space),          
            textcoords="offset points", 
            ha='center',                
            va=va)
In [10]:
flight_phases = ['Standing', 'Manoeuvring', 'Taxi', 'Take-off', 'Initial Climb', 'En route', 'Approach', 'Landing']
flight_phases_count = []

for flight_phase in flight_phases:
    flight_phases_count.append(df[df["FlightPhase"] == flight_phase]["FlightPhase"].count())
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12, 7))
ax.set_title("Aviation Accidents by Flight Phases From 2008 To March 2021\nData: ICAO")
ax.bar(flight_phases, flight_phases_count)
plt.xlabel('Flight Phase')
plt.ylabel('Number of Accidents')
add_value_labels(ax, 5)
plt.show()

Observation 2: Accidents tend to occur during the landing process of flights, accounting for more than double of the cases compared to other phases of flight. Generally, the phases of Manoeuvring and Initial Climb seem to be much safer than the others, accounting for only a few cases.¶

In [11]:
df["Country"].unique()
countries_count = []
for country in df["Country"].unique():
    obj = {
        "Country": country,
        "Number of Crashes": df[df["Country"] == country]["Country"].count(),
        "Number of Fatal Accidents": df[(df["Country"] == country) & (df["InjuryLevel"] == "Fatal")]["Country"].count()
    }
    countries_count.append(obj)
    
countries_count.sort(key=lambda x: x["Number of Crashes"], reverse=True)

countries = []
count = []
for i in range(10):
    countries.append(countries_count[i]["Country"])
    count.append(countries_count[i]["Number of Crashes"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (20, 7))
ax.set_title("Countries with Highest Total Number of Air Accidents From 2008 To March 2021\nData: ICAO")
ax.bar(countries, count)
add_value_labels(ax, 5)
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Number of Accidents')
plt.show()

countries_count.sort(key=lambda x: x["Number of Fatal Accidents"], reverse=True)
countries = []
count = []
for i in range(10):
    countries.append(countries_count[i]["Country"])
    count.append(countries_count[i]["Number of Fatal Accidents"])
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (20, 7))
ax.set_title("Countries with Highest Number of Fatal Accidents From 2008 To March 2021\nData: ICAO")
ax.bar(countries, count, color="darkorange")
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Number of Fatal Accidents')
plt.xticks(countries, rotation=45) 
add_value_labels(ax, 5)
plt.show()

Observation 3: A very large number of accidents occurred on the land of the United States, many times more than the other countries. This can be explained by the fact that the number of traffics on US airspace is always the highest all over the world. In contrast to that, only 9 over 319 accidents happened on the States are fatal. The highest number of fatal accidents is of Russian Federation, accounting up to 17 cases during 2008 and March 2021.¶

    countries_by_death_tolls.append(obj)

    count.append(int(countries_by_death_tolls[i]["Total death tolls"]))

plt.ylabel('Number of Deaths')

From the above chart, it is not enough to point out the change rules of aviation safety through the years. The number of people died from accidents tend to change unstably through the years.¶

cases_by_years = []
death_case_ratio = []
fatal_case_by_years = []

for year in years:
    cases_by_years.append(df[df["Year"] == year]["Year"].count())
    death_case_ratio.append(100 * df[(df["Year"] == year) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Year"].count() / df[df["Year"] == year]["Year"].count())
    fatal_case_by_years.append(df[(df["Year"] == year) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Year"].count())
    
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))      
plt.title("Number of Accidents and Fatal / Total Ratio by Years From 2008 to March 2021\nData: ICAO")
plt.bar(years, cases_by_years, color='lightblue')
plt.bar(years, fatal_case_by_years, color='lightgreen')
plt.ylabel('Number of Accidents')   
plt.legend(['Total Accidents', 'Fatal Accidents'])
plt.xticks(years)
for year, cases_by_year in zip(years, cases_by_years):
    plt.annotate('{}'.format(cases_by_year), xy=(year,cases_by_year), xytext=(8, 10), ha='right',
                textcoords='offset points')

x = years
axes2 = plt.twinx()
axes2.plot(years, death_case_ratio, color='orange', label='Sine')
axes2.set_ylabel('Fatal / Total Ratio (%)')
for year, death_case_ratio in zip(years, death_case_ratio):
    axes2.annotate('{:.2f}%'.format(death_case_ratio), xy=(year,death_case_ratio), xytext=(0, 10), ha='right',
                textcoords='offset points')
axes2.set_ylim(0, 50)

plt.show()

Plotting both the number of accidents and fatal / total ratio (ratio between number of fatal accidents among all accidents) and point out that the ratio tends to decreased through the years. It is clear that except 2010 and 2018, the number of fatal accidents tend to decreased through the years. The ratio increased at some points but that can be explained by the fact that the number of accidents in those years are different (the cases of 2020 and 2021).¶

Observation 4: It is not enough to fully assume that Civil Aviation in general has become progressively safer throughout the years 2008 to 2021, but in general, the number of accidents and especially the number of fatal accidents tend to decrease year by year.¶

This part gives some statistics about aircraft families of 2 largest aircraft manufacturers: Airbus and Boeing, in terms of the number of accidents occured and the number of fatal accidents occured.¶

In [17]:
aircraft_families_code = ['707', '717', '727', '737', '747', '757', '767', '777', '787',
                          'A300', '300', '310', '320', '321', '318', '319', '330', '340', '350', '380']
aircraft_families_name = ['Boeing 707', 'Boeing 717', 'Boeing 727', 'Boeing 737', 'Boeing 747', 'Boeing 757', 'Boeing 767', 'Boeing 777', 'Boeing 787',
                          'Airbus A300', 'Airbus A300',
                          'Airbus A310', 'Airbus A320', 'Airbus A321', 'Airbus A318', 'Airbus A319',
                          'Airbus A330', 'Airbus A340', 'Airbus A350', 'Airbus A380']
families = []
added = False

for row in df.iterrows():
    added = False
    get_model = row[1][3]
    for i, code in enumerate(aircraft_families_code):
        if get_model.find(code) != -1:
            families.append(aircraft_families_name[i])
            added = True
            break
    if (not added):
        families.append("Other")

df["Aircraft Family"] = families
In [18]:
accidents_count_by_types = dict()
fatal_count_by_types = dict()
statistic_count = dict()

obj_list = []

for family in df["Aircraft Family"].unique():
    if (family != 'Other'):
        obj = {
            "Family": family,
            "Accidents": df[df["Aircraft Family"] == family]["Aircraft Family"].count(),
            "Fatal": df[(df["Aircraft Family"] == family) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Aircraft Family"].count()
        }
        accidents_count_by_types[family] = df[df["Aircraft Family"] == family]["Aircraft Family"].count()
        fatal_count_by_types[family] = df[(df["Aircraft Family"] == family) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Aircraft Family"].count()
        obj_list.append(obj)
        
obj_list.sort(key=lambda x: x["Accidents"], reverse=True)
        
for obj in obj_list:
    if (obj["Family"] != 'Other'):
        family = obj["Family"]
        statistic_count[family] = [accidents_count_by_types[family], fatal_count_by_types[family]]
    
df_tmp = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(statistic_count, orient='index', columns = ['Total Accidents', 'Fatal Accidents'])
In [19]:
ax = df_tmp.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(20, 10), color=["green", "red"])
plt.title("Number of Accidents by Aircraft Families from Airbus and Boeing (2008 - March 2021)\nData: ICAO")
plt.legend(['Total Accidents', 'Fatal Accidents'])
add_value_labels(ax, 5)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.ylabel("Number of accidents")
plt.xlabel("Aircraft Family")
plt.show()

Observation 5: Clearly, Boeing 737 seems to be the most problematic aircraft family in this generation of Civil Aviation. Despite the fact that the number of flights operated by Boeing 737 can be much higher than other families, the number is still "huge". Generally, Airbus seems to be a safer choice.¶

The final part of the report statisticize information about the distribution of accidents on different months, days and dates.¶

In [20]:
time_df = pd.DataFrame()
time_df['Month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).month
time_df['Day'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).day
time_df['Merged'] = df['Date'].dt.strftime("%d/%m")

months = []
days = []
merge_days = time_df['Merged'].unique()
merge_days_obj = []

for i in range(1, 13):
    obj = {
        "Month": i,
        "Accidents": df[pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).month == i]["Date"].count(),
        "Fatal": df[(pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).month == i) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Date"].count()
    }
    months.append(obj)
    
for i in range(1, 32):
    obj = {
        "Day": i,
        "Accidents": df[pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).day == i]["Date"].count(),
        "Fatal": df[(pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Date']).day == i) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Date"].count()
    }
    days.append(obj)
    
for merge_day in merge_days:
    obj = {
        "Date": merge_day,
        "Accidents": df[df['Date'].dt.strftime("%d/%m") == merge_day]["Date"].count(),
        "Fatal": df[(df['Date'].dt.strftime("%d/%m") == merge_day) & (df["Fatalities"] > 0)]["Date"].count()
    }
    merge_days_obj.append(obj)
    
days.sort(key=lambda x: x["Accidents"], reverse=True)
merge_days_obj.sort(key=lambda x: x["Accidents"], reverse=True)

Observation 6: Air travel seems to be more risky during the Winter (Dec to Feb) with slighly higher number of accidents occured. Also in general, more accidents happened during the beginning or the end of months. However, this information is not usable to conclude any useful knowledge since the occurence of aviation accidents depend on many factors, especially the "human factor" that accounts up to a high percentage of all aviation accidents.¶
